\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \lor  I_r:\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{(p \land  q) \lor  r\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \lor  E^1:\quad }}
\TrinaryInfC{\ensuremath{(p \land  q) \lor  r\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \rightarrow  I^2:\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{(q \lor  r) \rightarrow  ((p \land  q) \lor  r)\vphantom{|}}}
\DP

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
For example, classical logic, K3, LP, and FDE all validate every instance of what are sometimes called the "De Morgan laws":

eg (A \land B) \;/\; 
eg A \lor 
eg B

eg (A \lor B) \;/\; 
eg A \land 
eg B

eg A \lor 
eg B \;/\; 
eg (A \land B)

eg A \land 
eg B \;/\; 
eg (A \lor B)

